        <!-- Key Actions -->
        <div class="card" style="margin-bottom: 20px;">
            <h3>Key Actions & Safety Considerations</h3>
            <ul class="actions-list"><li>Monitor natural avalanche releases actively, particularly in the Shale chute area.</li><li>Use conservative route selection, especially above the 1600m snowline where hazards are accentuated.</li><li>Maintain vigilance as the moderate hazard in the alpine zone may increase with the upcoming warm atmospheric river event.</li><li>Follow groomed routes where conditions are track-packed and stable, but reassess if new releases are observed.</li><li>Regularly check updated forecasts and be prepared to adjust plans based on evolving stability conditions.</li></ul>
        </div>

        <!-- Closing Summary -->
        
                    <div class="summary-card">
                        <h3>Closing Summary</h3>
                        <div class="summary-text">This report outlines observed natural size 2 storm slab avalanches with moderate hazard ratings in the alpine zone, primarily driven by recent precipitation and the influence of a warm atmospheric river event. Cautious travel with an emphasis on conservative decision-making remains paramount as conditions may evolve rapidly. Operators and guides should prioritize safe, well-assessed routes above 1600m and re-assess terrain as weather conditions change. Stay updated and be prepared for potential increases in instability, ensuring that all backcountry trips are planned with current hazard awareness in mind.</div>
